Experiment:

You are comparing the seed yields of four potential pistillate parents in a bell pepper breeding program: G1, G2, G3, and G4. Besides differences among the genotypes, you are interested in the effects of fertilizer rates and time of pollination on seed production. You plant two plants of each of the four genotypes in pots and randomly place them on the benches of your greenhouse. Next, the pots are randomly assigned a pollination time: morning (AM), noon (N), or afternoon (PM). Finally, each pot is fertigated throughout seed development at a low (F1), medium (F2), medium-high (F3), or high (F4) rate. There is an equal representation of all Fertilizer-Time-Genotype treatments. The plants were pruned to two fruit per plant and at maturity, the fruit are harvested, the seeds counted, and the average seeds per fruit are calculated.

Note: Since you only have two replicates per treatment, it’s not really possible to verify the ANOVA assumptions of normality and homogeneity of variances, so we’ll skip that.

  1. Describe the design of this experiment in detail.
Design: 4x3x4 factorial arranged in a completely randomized design.
Response Variable: Seeds per fruit
Experimental Unit: Pot
Factor No. Levels Description
1 4 Fertilizer rate
2 3 Time of pollination
3 4 Pepper genotypes
Subsamples? YES The average seeds per fruit per plant are calculated from two fruits per plant. Since we did not specify whether the seeds from two fruits were combined and then averaged, you can also say that there were no subsamples.
  1. Use an ANOVA to test for interactions. How many potential interactions are there? Which interactions are significant? When drawing conclusions, be sure to adjust your alpha to control the EER for interactions.
contrasts(data_4.1$Fert) = contr.sum
contrasts(data_4.1$Time) = contr.sum
contrasts(data_4.1$Geno) = contr.sum

model = lm(Seeds ~ Fert*Time*Geno, data_4.1)
anova(model)

Since this is a three-way factorial, there are three potential two-way interactions (Fertilizer:Time, Fertilizer:Genotype, and Time:Genotype) plus the Fertilizer:Time:Genotype three-way interaction. The adjusted CER for testing the four interactions is 0.0127. According to the ANOVA, only the Time:Genotype interaction was significant (p = 0.0063).

  1. Make interaction plots for each of the two-way interactions. The first is provided for you. Since this is a three-way design, you will produce plots of the interaction for each level of the third factor. Discuss how each plot relates to the results of the ANOVA (i.e. which plots appear to show an interaction, and does this agree with the ANOVA results?). For extra credit, make a plot of the three-way interaction.
ggplot(data_4.1,aes(x=Geno,y=Seeds,group = Time)) +

ggplot(data_4.1,aes(x=Geno,y=Seeds,group = Fert)) +

ggplot(data_4.1,aes(x=Fert,y=Seeds,group = Time)) +
    geom_smooth(aes(color = Time)) + facet_wrap(~Geno)

Remember, each value on these figures is the average of only two values, so the plots are only of marginal descriptive value. When we look at the Time:Geno interaction at each level of Fert, the clear interaction is at Fert2, where seed yield in Geno2 and Geno3 appears to be significantly lower than yield in Geno1 and Geno4 with AM pollination, but similar with N and PM pollination. This relationship is also seen between AM and PM pollination times in Fert1.

For the Fert:Geno interaction, significant initeractions are difficult to distinguish (this concurs with the ANOVA results). In these plots, the shaded regions (2SE’s) appear to overlap in all cases.

The the Fert:Time plots, we see some separation of the lines, but no clear examples of lines that are not parallel, also consistent with the ANOVA.

Now, how do we look at the 3-way interaction? Well, what is the 3-way interaction? It’s when the difference between levels of a first factor changes among levels of a second factor, and then those changes change across levels of a third factor (confusing!). To look at this, we can make an interaction plot of the differences among levels of the first factor across the combinations of the other two factors. We have to make a different plot for each of the contrasts in the first factor. We don’t see much evidence of three-way interactions in either of the following plots. See the Readings on SmartSite for clearer examples.

data_4.1_AM = subset(data_4.1,Time == 'AM')
data_4.1_N = subset(data_4.1,Time == 'N')
data_4.1_PM = subset(data_4.1,Time == 'PM')

data_4.1_N$AM_vs_N = data_4.1_AM$Seeds - data_4.1_N$Seeds
data_4.1_N$PM_vs_N = data_4.1_PM$Seeds - data_4.1_N$Seeds


ggplot(data_4.1_N,aes(x=Fert, y=AM_vs_N, group = Geno)) +
    geom_smooth(aes(color = Geno)) 

ggplot(data_4.1_N,aes(x=Fert, y=PM_vs_N, group = Geno)) +
    geom_smooth(aes(color = Geno))

    • If there is a three-way interaction involving genotype, this means that the differences among genotypes change depending on the particular combination of each of the other two factors. Follow the proceedure from Step 4 in Lab 4 to run HSD.test for each combination of fertilization rate and pollination time. Hint: make a new factor called Fert_Time and subset based on each of the 12 levels of this factor.
    • If there are any significant two-way interactions between genotype and another factor, then follow the lab proceedure above to compare the genotypes within each level of that other factor. Repeate for each factor that has a two-way interaction with genotype.
    • If there are no significant interactions involving genotype but there is a significant main effect, use HSD.test to test for differences among levels. Use the full model and specify the argument trt as Geno.
    • If there are no significant interactions involving genotype, and there is not a significant main effect, report the genotype differences as zero.
    • Note: Consider the number of tests that you are doing in each step and adjust your \(\alpha\) level accordingly. You can adjust \(\alpha\) individually for ANOVA and for the Tukey HSD comparisons.
    • For your “report”, first state whether genotype interacts with any other factor, and then provide a table of letters signifying significant genotype differences as described in the appropriate section.
library(agricolae)

#Since the only significant interaction is the Time:Geno interaction, we will compare Genotype means at each level of the Time factor.

#Extract the error df and MSE from the original model:
anova_4 = anova(model)
DFerror = anova_4['Residuals',"Df"]
MSerror = anova_4['Residuals',"Mean Sq"]
alpha_group = 1 - (1 - 0.05)^(1/3)

#Subset the data by Time, and compare Genotypes at each Time:
with(subset(data_4.1, Time =='AM'), 
     HSD.test(Seeds, Geno, DFerror = DFerror, MSerror = MSerror, alpha = alpha_group)$groups)
##   trt    means M

## 1  G3 210.8504  a

## 4  G2 198.8697  b
list_of_times = levels(data_4.1$Time)  
tukey_table = sapply(list_of_times,function(time){
  with(
    subset(data_4.1,Time == time), {  
     groups = HSD.test(
                        Seeds, 
                        Geno,  
                        DFerror=DFerror,MSerror = MSerror, alpha = alpha_group)$groups
     groups = groups[order(groups$trt),]
     groups$M
    })
})
colnames(tukey_table) = paste('Time',1:3)
rownames(tukey_table) = paste('Geno',1:4)
tukey_table

Based on the ANOVA, there was a significant Time:Genotype interaction (p = 0.0063). Thus, we tested differences among genotypes at each time of pollination. In pollinations performed in the morning, the fruits of genotypes 1 and 4 contained significantly more seeds than genotypes 2 and 3. In pollinations performed at noon, genotypes 1 and 4 produced the most seed; however, genotype 4 did not produce significantly more seed than genotype 3. Seed production in genotype 2 was not significantly different from genotype 3. Lastly, genotype 3 produced the most seed in afternoon pollinations, but only significantly more than genotype 2. In afternoon pollinations, seed yield in genotypes 1 and 4 was not different from genotype 2 or 3.

# make your contrast matrix: 
contrast_matrix <- cbind(
  AM_vs_N = c(1, -1, 0),
  PM_vs_N = c(0, -1, 1))

contrasts(data_4.1$Time) = inverse_contrast_matrix

According to the contrasts performed, seed yield was significantly lower with morning pollinations compared with noon pollinations for each of the genotypes (corrected CER = 6.39 x 10-3). These differences ranged from 12 seeds/fruit in Geno4 to almost 20 seeds/fruit in Geno 2. Seed yield between afternoon and noon pollinations were much more similar, though. Only Geno3 fruit possessed significantly more seed (13 seeds/fruit) when pollinated in the afternoon than when pollinated at noon.

  1. What conclusions do you draw about the best way to maximize Seed production?

Since we found no interactions involving fertilizer, let’s take a look at differences among Fert levels with Tukey’s test, first:

with(data_4.1, HSD.test(Seeds, Fert, DFerror = DFerror, MSerror = MSerror)$groups)
##   trt    means M
## 1  F3 206.7727 a
## 2  F4 203.5801 a
## 3  F2 196.4562 b
## 4  F1 186.3608 c

According to Tukey’s test Fert3 and Fert4 resulted in significantly higher seed yields than Fert1 and Fert2. Since seed yield was similar between Fert3 and Fert4, we may as well use Fert3 to optimize yield and save little cost on fertilizer.

# Now, since there is an interaction between Genotype and Time, we need to decide which combination(s) to recommend. Above we tested if the the times were different for each genotype. But to compare all combinations of Time and Genotype, it's better to use the Tukey procedure on all combinations of these factors
Tukey_Time_Geno = HSD.test(model,c('Time','Geno'),group = T)

This analysis says that in our data the PM:G3 combination produced the most seeds, but several time:genotype combinations were not statistically distinguishable (all those with an a above). The only consistent conclusion here is that all AM polinations had significantly lower seed production than other treatments. So we can recommend against that polination time.
